Reasoning: The paper deals with complexity theory and algorithms, specifically classical and quantum query algorithms, and their relationship to rational functions with nonnegative coefficients. This falls under the scope of computational complexity (cs.CC) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG) in its discussion of polynomial approximations. Additionally, the paper touches on discrete mathematics (cs.DM) in its analysis of symmetric functions.
